Perfect! I found the bug. Let me analyze the code:

In the `MessageEncoder.default()` method (lines 17-25):
```python
def default(self, obj):
    if isinstance(obj, Message):
        # Using 0/1 here instead of False/True to produce more compact json
        is_safedata = 1 if isinstance(obj.message, SafeData) else 0
        message = [self.message_key, is_safedata, obj.level, obj.message]
        if obj.extra_tags:  # <-- THIS IS THE BUG
            message.append(obj.extra_tags)
        return message
    return super().default(obj)
```

The problem is on line 22: `if obj.extra_tags:` - this checks for truthiness, so an empty string `""` is falsy and won't be appended to the message.

In the `MessageDecoder.process_messages()` method (lines 33-43):
```python
def process_messages(self, obj):
    if isinstance(obj, list) and obj:
        if obj[0] == MessageEncoder.message_key:
            if obj[1]:
                obj[3] = mark_safe(obj[3])
            return Message(*obj[2:])  # <-- This creates the Message
        return [self.process_messages(item) for item in obj]
    if isinstance(obj, dict):
        return {key: self.process_messages(value)
                for key, value in obj.items()}
    return obj
```

When decoding, it does `Message(*obj[2:])`. If `extra_tags` was not appended during encoding (because it was an empty string), then the `obj` list will only have 4 elements: `[message_key, is_safedata, level, message]`. So `obj[2:]` would be `[level, message]`, and the Message constructor would be called with just these two arguments.


I'll investigate the Message class constructor to understand its parameters.

